  "footnotes": [
    "Polotsk Principality: The most powerful early Belarusian principality; under Vseslav Brjachislavich (1044–1101) it briefly raided Novgorod and Pskov; maintained de facto independence from Kievan Rus.",
    "Grand Duchy of Lithuania: Despite its name, the majority of GDL territory and population was Ruthenian (Belarusian/Ukrainian); Old Belarusian (Chancery Slavonic) served as the official administrative language.",
    "Belarusian People's Republic (BNR, 1918): Declared independence on 25 March 1918 under German occupation; never controlled its full claimed territory; dissolved without lasting recognition; 25 March remains Belarusian Freedom Day.",
    "The Deluge (1654–1667): Russo-Polish War and Swedish invasion devastated the Grand Duchy of Lithuania's Belarusian core; Belarus lost an estimated 40–50% of its population.",
    "Operation Bagration (1944): Soviet summer offensive that liberated Belarus from Nazi occupation; Belarus lost approximately 25–30% of its total prewar population during the occupation (roughly 2.2 million dead).",
    "UN Founding Member: Despite being part of the Soviet Union, the Byelorussian SSR was granted separate UN membership in 1945, along with the Ukrainian SSR, as a diplomatic compromise recognising Soviet territorial losses."
  ]
